<section xml:id="section-graphing-equations">

    <title>Graphing Equations</title>
    
    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-label-and-scale-graphs" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-different-scales" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-table-of-values" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-plot-points-from-table" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-emphasize-graph-visual-representation-of-solution-set" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-create-graph-linear-model" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-interpret-graphs" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-graph-lines-with-ordered-pairs" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-interpret-intercepts-in-context" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-create-tables-and-graphs-in-context" /></li>
         </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>We have learned how to plot points in a coordinate system. Next, we will learn how to graph <em>lines</em> and <em>curves</em> that represent solutions to equations with two variables. We will begin by graphing equations that are written in form <m>y=\ldots</m> with only <m>x</m>-variables on the right, like <m>y=-2x+5</m> and <m>y=x^2</m>. These equations are not difficult to graph, as you'll see.</p>

    <figure>
        <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        <video youtube="33kaIpvncag" />
    </figure>

    <p>A <term>graph</term> of an equation is a graphical representation of that equation's solution set. For example, the graph of <m>y=-2x+3</m> is shown in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-full">Figure</xref>. The graph plots the ordered pairs whose <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-coordinates will make <m>y=-2x+3</m> true. The table in <xref ref="figure-check-points-for-line">Figure</xref> shows that many points on the graph make the equation true.</p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-check-points-for-line">
        <caption />
        <p><md>
            <mrow>y\amp=-2x+3\amp\amp(x,y)</mrow>
            <mrow>\hline\substitute{5}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\substitute{-1})+3\amp\amp(\substitute{-1},\substitute{5})</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{3}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\substitute{0})+3\amp\amp(\substitute{0},\substitute{3})</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{1}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\substitute{1})+3\amp\amp(\substitute{1},\substitute{1})</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{-1}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\substitute{2})+3\amp\amp(\substitute{2},\substitute{-1})</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{-3}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\substitute{3})+3\amp\amp(\substitute{3},\substitute{-3})</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{-5}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\substitute{4})+3\amp\amp(\substitute{4},\substitute{-5})</mrow>
        </md></p>
    </figure>

    <p><xref ref="figure-check-points-for-line">Table</xref> tells us that the points <m>(-1,5)</m>, <m>(0,3)</m>, <m>(1,1)</m>, <m>(2,-1)</m>, <m>(3,-3)</m>, and <m>(4,-5)</m> are all solutions to the equation <m>y=-2x+3</m>, and so they should all be shaded as part of that equation's graph. You can see them in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-sparse">Figure</xref>. But there are many more points that make the equation true. More points are plotted in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-more">Figure</xref>. Even more points are plotted in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-full">Figure</xref> <mdash /> so many, that together the points look like a straight line.</p>

    <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%">
        <caption>Graphs of the Equation <m>y=-2x+3</m></caption>
        <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-sparse">
            <caption>A few points<ellipsis/></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,5)} node[rotate=30,left]{$(-1,5)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,3)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(0,3)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,1)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(1,1)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(2,-1)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,-3)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(3,-3)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-5)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(4,-5)$};;
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-more">
            <caption>More points<ellipsis /></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1.5,6) (-1.2,5.4) (-1,5) (-0.8,4.6) (-0.3, 3.6) (0,3) (0.4,2.2) (1,1) (1.1,0.8) (1.7,-0.4) (2,-1) (2.3,-1.6) (2.6,-2.2) (3,-3) (3.5,-4) (4,-5) (4.3,-5.6) (4.8,-6.6)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-full">
            <caption>So many points it looks like a straight line</caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot+[domain=-2:5,soliddot,samples=50] {-2*x+3};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>Generalizing<ellipsis /></p>

    <remark>
        <p>The graph of an equation shades all the points <m>(x,y)</m> that make the equation true once the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values are substituted in. Typically, there are <em>so many</em> points shaded, that the final graph appears to be a continuous line or curve that you could draw with one stroke of a pen.</p>
    </remark>

