    <exercise>
        <webwork>
            <setup>
                <var name="$truefalse[0]">
                    <set>
                        <member correct="yes">\text{true}</member>
                        <member>\text{false}</member>
                    </set>
                </var>
                <var name="$truefalse[1]">
                    <set>
                        <member>\text{true}</member>
                        <member correct="yes">\text{false}</member>
                    </set>
                </var>
                <var name="$shaded[0]">
                    <set>
                        <member correct="yes">\text{shaded}</member>
                        <member>\text{not shaded}</member>
                    </set>
                </var>
                <var name="$shaded[1]">
                    <set>
                        <member>\text{shaded}</member>
                        <member correct="yes">\text{not shaded}</member>
                    </set>
                </var>
                <var name="$y[0]"><static>-2</static></var>
                <var name="$y[1]"><static>-7</static></var>
                <var name="$x[0]"><static>5</static></var>
                <var name="$x[1]"><static>-10</static></var>
                <var name="$f"><static>-\frac{3}{5}x+1</static></var>
                <var name="$right[0]"><static>1</static></var>
                <var name="$right[1]"><static>\frac{2}{5}</static></var>
                <pg-code>
                    Context()->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                    @y=(-2,-7);
                    @x=(5,-10);
                    Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0);
                    $f=Compute("-(3/5)x+1");
                    @right=map{$f->substitute(x=>Formula($x[$_]))}(0,1);
                    @truefalse=(PopUp(['?','true','false'],1),PopUp(['?','true','false'],2));
                    @shaded=(PopUp(['?','shaded','not shaded'],1),PopUp(['?','shaded','not shaded'],2));
                </pg-code>
            </setup>
            <statement>
                <p>Decide whether the points <m>(5,-2)</m> and <m>(-10,-7)</m> will be on the graph of the equation <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m></p>
                <p>At <m>(5,-2)</m>:</p>
                <table>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="right" />
                        <col/>
                        <col/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><var name="$y[0]" width="1" /></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><var name="$right[0]" width="10" /></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>This equation is <var name="$truefalse[0]" form="popup" />, and <m>(5,-2)</m> is <var name="$shaded[0]" form="popup" /> on the graph of <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m>.</p>
                <p>At <m>(-10,-7)</m>:</p>
                <table>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="right" />
                        <col/>
                        <col/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><var name="$y[1]" width="1" /></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><var name="$right[1]" width="10" /></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>This equation is <var name="$truefalse[1]" form="popup" />, and <m>(5,-2)</m> is <var name="$shaded[1]" form="popup" /> on the graph of <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>If the point <m>(5,-2)</m> is on <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{,}</m> once we substitute <m>x=5</m> and <m>y=-2</m> into the line's equaiton, the equation should be true. Let's try:<md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{3}{5}x+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-\frac{3}{5}(5)+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=} -3+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=} -2</mrow>
                </md>Because this last equation is true, we can definitively say that <m>(5,-2)</m> is on the graph of <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>However if we substitute <m>x=-10</m> and <m>y=-7</m> into the equation, it leads to <m>-7=7</m>, which is false. This definitively tells us that <m>(-10,-7)</m> is not on the graph.</p>
            </solution>
        </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>So to make our own graph of an equation with two variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we can choose some reasonable <m>x</m>-values, then calculate the corresponding <m>y</m>-values, and then plot the <m>(x,y)</m>-pairs as points. For many (not-so-complicated) algebraic equations, connecting those points with a smooth curve will produce an excellent graph.</p>

    <example>
        <p>Let's plot a graph for the equation <m>y=-2x+5</m>. We use a table to organize our work:</p>

        <sidebyside>
            <caption>Making a table for <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
            <table>
                <caption>Set up the table</caption>
                <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                        <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                        <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                        <cell>Point</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(-2,9)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(-1,7)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(0,5)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(1,3)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="none">
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(2,1)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <table>
                <caption>Complete the table</caption>
                <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                        <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                        <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                        <cell>Point</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(-2,9)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(-1,7)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(0,5)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(1,3)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="none">
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(2,1)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>We use points from the table to graph the equation. First, plot each point carefully. Then, connect the points with a smooth curve. Here, the curve is a straight line. Lastly, we can communicate that the graph extends further by sketching arrows on both ends of the line.</p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
            <caption>Graphing the Equation <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
            <figure>
                <caption>Use points from the table</caption>
                <image>
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                        xtick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        ytick=,
                                        minor ytick=,]
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <figure>
                <caption>Connect the points in whatever pattern is apparent</caption>
                <image>
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                        xtick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        ytick=,
                                        minor ytick=,]
                                \addplot+[domain=-2.5:3] {-2*x+5};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <remark>
        <p>Note that our choice of <m>x</m>-values is arbitrary. As long as we determine the coordinates of enough points to indicate the behavior of the graph, we may choose whichever <m>x</m>-values we like. For simpler caclulations, people often start with the integers from <m>-2</m> to <m>2</m>. However sometimes the equation has context that suggests using other <m>x</m>-values, as in the next example.</p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="example-gas-mileage">
        <statement>
            <p>One car's gas tank holds <quantity><mag>14</mag><unit base="gallon" /></quantity> of fuel. Over the course of a long road trip, that car uses its fuel at an average rate of <quantity><mag>0.032</mag><unit base="gallon"/><per base="mile"/></quantity>. If a driver fills the tank at the beginning of a long trip, then the amount of fuel remaining in the tank, <m>y</m>, after driving <m>x</m> miles is given by the equation <m>y=14-0.032x</m>. Make a suitable table of values and graph this equation.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Choosing <m>x</m>-values from <m>-2</m> to <m>2</m>, as in our previous example, wouldn't make sense here. Driving a negative number of miles is not possible, and any long road trip is longer than <m>2</m> miles. So in this context, choose <m>x</m>-values that reflect the number of miles one might drive in a day.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <table>
                    <caption>Make the table</caption>
                    <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                        <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell halign="center"><m>y=14-0.032x</m></cell>
                            <cell>Point</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>13.36</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(20,13.36)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>50</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>12.4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(50,12.4)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>80</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>11.44</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(80,11.44)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>100</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>10.8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(100,10.8)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="none">
                            <cell><m>200</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>7.6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(200,7.6)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Make the graph</caption>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[xmin=0,xmax=250,
                                            ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                            xlabel={$x$ (miles)},
                                            ylabel={$y$ (gallons)},
                                            xtick=,
                                            minor xtick={0,10,...,250},
                                            ytick=,
                                            minor ytick={0,1,...,20},
                                            clip=false,
                                            grid=major,
                                            axis line style={->}]
                                    \addplot+[domain=0:250,->] {14-0.032*x};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(20,13.36)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(20,13.36)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(50,12.4)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(50,12.4)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(80,11.44)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(80,11.44)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(100,10.8)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(100,10.8)$};;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(200,7.6)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(200,7.6)$};;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <aside>
        <title>Units on axes labels</title>
        <p>In the graph from <xref ref="example-gas-mileage">Example</xref>, notice how both axes indicate units that help describe the meaning of each variable. Whenever a graph has real-world context, be sure to label both axes clearly with both variable name (like <m>x</m>) and units.</p>
    </aside>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Build a table and graph the equation <m>y=x^2\text{.}</m> Use <m>x</m>-values from <m>-3</m> to <m>3</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <table>
                    <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                        <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell halign="center"><m>y=x^2</m></cell>
                            <cell>Point</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-3)^2=9</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-3,9)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2)^2=4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2,4)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1)^2=1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1,1)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0)^2=0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0,0)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(1)^2=1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0,1)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(2)^2=4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(2,4)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="none">
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(3)^2=9</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(3,9)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                        <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-3,9), (-2,4),(-1,1),(0,0),(1,1),(2,4),(3,9)</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[ymin=-2,ymax=10,
                                            ytick=,
                                            minor ytick={-2,-1,...,10},]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-3.16:3.16] {x^2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,9)} node[left]{$(-3,9)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,4)} node[left]{$(-2,4)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,1)} node[left]{$(-1,1)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[below]{$(0,0)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,1)} node[right]{$(1,1)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,4)} node[right]{$(2,4)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,9)} node[right]{$(3,9)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>In this example, the points do not fall on a straight line. Many algebraic equations have graphs that are non-linear, where the points do not fall on a straight line. Since each <m>x</m>-value corresponds to a single <m>y</m>-value (the square of <m>x</m>) we connected the points with a smooth curve, sketching from left to right.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

